Regression and Model Validation

Regression

The data “students2014” is about the students attitude toward statistics. The data consists of information about students’ gender, student ages, deep approach(deep), surface appoarch(surf), strategic approach(stra), attitude toward statistics, points from exam and the students’ gender. WIth the data “students2014”, you can figure out that what variables affect the exam points through linear regression analysis.*

You can read the data and name the data “students2014” with the code “read.table”

students2014<-read.table(“http://s3.amazonaws.com/assets.datacamp.com/production/course_2218/datasets/learning2014.txt”, sep=“,”, header=TRUE )

Through the codes “dim()” and “str()”, you can take a look at the dimension and structure of data.

dim(students2014)

str(students2014)

You can compare all variables to find out what variable affect the most to the exam points, how the variables are distributed and how they are related to using the code “ggpairs()”.

library(GGally) library(ggplot2)

pairs(students2014[-1], col=(students2014$gender)) p <- ggpairs(students2014, mapping = aes(col=gender, alpha=0.3), lower = list(combo = wrap(“facethist”, bins = 20))) p

In outputs, three variables,“attitude”, “stra” and “surf” are the most correlated to the exam points, and looks linear. To test the liearity, we will fte a model with three variables.

model1<-lm(points ~ attitude+stra+surf, data=students2014) summary(model1)

Output of the summary of model1

Call: lm(formula = points ~ attitude + stra + surf, data = students2014)

Residuals: Min 1Q Median 3Q Max -17.1550 -3.4346 0.5156 3.6401 10.8952

Coefficients: Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|) (Intercept) 11.0171 3.6837 2.991 0.00322 attitude 3.3952 0.5741 5.913 1.93e-08 stra 0.8531 0.5416 1.575 0.11716 surf -0.5861 0.8014 -0.731 0.46563

(Intercept) ** attitude *** stra
surf
— Signif. codes:
0 ‘’ 0.001 ’’ 0.01 ’’ 0.05 ‘.’ 0.1 ‘’ 1

Residual standard error: 5.296 on 162 degrees of freedom Multiple R-squared: 0.2074, Adjusted R-squared: 0.1927 F-statistic: 14.13 on 3 and 162 DF, p-value: 3.156e-08

In this model, “Stra” and “suft” among three explanatory variables are not significantly related to exam points based on p-value. So, excluding the two variables, the model is fitted with “attitude” once again.

model2<-lm(points ~ attitude, data=students2014) summary(model2)

Output of the model2

Call: lm(formula = points ~ attitude, data = students2014)

Residuals: Min 1Q Median 3Q Max -16.9763 -3.2119 0.4339 4.1534 10.6645

Coefficients: Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)
(Intercept) 11.6372 1.8303 6.358 1.95e-09 attitude 3.5255 0.5674 6.214 4.12e-09 — Signif. codes: 0 ‘’ 0.001 ’’ 0.01 ’’ 0.05 ‘.’ 0.1 ‘’ 1

Residual standard error: 5.32 on 164 degrees of freedom Multiple R-squared: 0.1906, Adjusted R-squared: 0.1856 F-statistic: 38.61 on 1 and 164 DF, p-value: 4.119e-09

In model2, the summary indicates that the relationship between the exam point and attitude is significant correlated at 0.00000000412 p-value. And the mulitple R-squared value is 0.1906 so this model can explain 20% of the relataionship between the exam points and attitude.

Assumption of Model and Model validation

By analyzing the residuals of the model, you can explore the validity of the model assumptions. par(mfrow=c(2,2)) plot(model2, which = c(1,2,5))

In the plot " residutals vs FItted values“, the variace are constant. But, some values look outliers. In leverage of observations, there are still some outliers affecting errors. In normality of Q-Q plot, the residulass are linearly distributed, which means the errors of the model are normally distributed.

draw a biplot of the principan component representation and the original variables

s<-summary(pca_human)

rounded percentages of variance captured by each PC

pca_pr<-round(1*s$importance[2,], digits=1)

print out the percentages of variance

pca_pr
## PC1 PC2 PC3 PC4 PC5 PC6 PC7 PC8 
## 0.5 0.2 0.1 0.1 0.1 0.0 0.0 0.0

create object pc_lab to be used as axis labels

pc_lab<-paste0(names(pca_pr), "(", pca_pr, "%)")

draw a biplot

biplot(pca_human, cex=c(0.8,1), col=c("grey40", "deeppink2"), xlab=pc_lab[1], ylab=pc_lab[2])

Unstandaized variables looks out of ranges because PCA is sensitive to the relatives scallings of the orginal variables and assumes that feature with larger varianace are more important than variables with smaller variabnce.
